				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\kappa =\rho {C}_{{\rm{p}}}D$$\end{document}Heat capacity measurements were performed on a small (66.1 mg) single crystal of SnS using a differential scanning calorimeter (DSC 404 F1 Pegasus, Netzsch). Measurements were performed under flowing Ar with a heating rate of 10 K/min. Three consecutive DSC runs were performed with empty crucible (baseline), sapphire (reference) and SnS (sample) in order to calculate the heat capacity according to DIN 51007. Thermal diffusivity was measured using the light flash method with a Netzsch LFA 467HT apparatus. X-ray Laue was used to align a large single crystal ingot of SnS for cutting. Three different pieces (plate-like shapes) were then cut, each with a different principal crystallographic axis perpendicular to the plate face. The thickness of these pieces ranged from 1.25 to 2.00 mm and they were coated with graphite, to improve absorption and emissivity, prior to measurement. Three measurements were taken at each temperature in order to calculate the mean D and data was also recorded on cooling to confirm reproducibility. Thermal diffusivity was calculated from the measured sample response according to the Cape-Lehman method. Sample density was taken to be 5.22 g cm−3.
